Mary,

Sending this from home so please forgive the informality. I wanted you
to hear this from me before the operations ticket lands in your inbox
tomorrow morning.

Cordell Hall is not going to be ready. The electrical work overran and
the facilities contractor is not willing to sign off on the room in time
for the conference. We have moved your keynote to Theatre B in the lower
level north wing. It is smaller, three hundred twenty seats rather than
the four hundred and eighty in Cordell, but the acoustics are actually
better for a spoken piece and the projection is sharper.

Two things I need you to know because they affect what you prepare.

First the pre panel that Aisha Rahman was going to moderate before your
slot has been folded into your session. There will not be a separate
introducer panel. You will take the stage at two in the afternoon and
you will have the full hour that was previously split between the panel
and your slot. Aisha is fine with the change, I spoke with her at length
and she is grateful to be freed up for the closing plenary.

Second because you now have the full hour rather than the forty five
minutes that were left after the panel intro, you have room to breathe
in your talk. You do not need to lengthen it and no one will notice if
you land at fifty two minutes rather than sixty. But you do have the
room if a story wants to run.

The AV walkthrough is at twelve thirty. I have you on the schedule for
that already, no action needed.

I know you are careful about numbers and I want to say plainly that the
data you cite in this talk should hold up to a trustee asking about it
afterward. Two of ours are going to be in the room and you know how
Douglas is.

Rest well.

Reggie

